Text semantic similarity¶

Steps

  1. Transform a sentence to a set of vectors based on it's semantic meaning
  2. Calculate vectors' similarity

Step1:
Transform a sentence to a set of vectors based on it's semantic meaning
We need to choose an algorithm to realize it

Sentence-Transformers Methods
Measuring text similarity using BERT

Reference:
https://arxiv.org/abs/1810.04805 (Original article, Google AI Language)
https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2021/05/measuring-text-similarity-using-bert/ (A tutorial)
https://zhuanlan.zhihu.com/p/51413773 (A tutorial)

BERT: Pre-training of Deep Bidirectional Transformers for Language Understanding
Key words: pre-training, deep (learning), bidirectional, transformers, language understanding

pre-training: Language model for improving natural language processing tasks;
deep: has 12 layers;
bidrectional: can predict the mask word before and after;
transformer: transform sentence to vectors;
landuage understanding: can understanding the sentence's semantic meaning.

Return a vector comprising 768 digits.

(Note: there are many language understanding models, BERT is just one of them. Each model has different performance and is focused on specific apects. Choosing a suitable model is tricky, though)

Step2:
Compute similarity
Cosine distance is commonly used in NLP area

Define some useful functions

In [26]:
## write a function to melt dependent data
def melt_df(df_temp):
    df_size = len(df_temp)
    df_ls = list()
    for i in range(0,df_size):
        for j in range(i+1,df_size):
            df_ls.append(df_temp.iloc[j,i])
    return df_ls

## write a function to do permutation test on dependent data
def permu_test_new(df1, df2, n_times):
    df_per_corr = list()
    for i in range(n_times):
        df1_size = len(df1)
        df1_vec = list()
        for j in range(0, df1_size):
            np_temp = np.array(df1.iloc[(j+1):,j])
            np.random.shuffle(np_temp)
            for k in range(len(np_temp)):
                df1_vec.append(np_temp[k])   
        df2_size = len(df2)
        df2_vec = list()
        for j in range(0, df2_size):
            np_temp = np.array(df2.iloc[(j+1):,j])
            np.random.shuffle(np_temp)
            for k in range(len(np_temp)):
                df2_vec.append(np_temp[k])
        df_per_r_temp = spearmanr(df1_vec,df2_vec)[0]
        df_per_corr.append(df_per_r_temp)
    return df_per_corr

Calculate spearman correlation between score RDM and review RDM

In [27]:
score_vec = melt_df(df_score_rdm)
review_vec = melt_df(df_review_rdm)
# calculate spearman r
review_corr = spearmanr(score_vec, review_vec)
review_corr
Out[27]:
SpearmanrResult(correlation=0.21756001375847686, pvalue=0.0)

Permutation test

In [28]:
df_per_corr = permu_test_new(df_score_rdm, df_review_rdm, 5000)
## plot the distribution
# import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.hist(df_per_corr, bins=50)
plt.title("Permutation distribution of test statistic")
plt.xlabel("Value of Statistic")
plt.ylabel("Frequency")
plt.show()

The correlation value is higher than chance level

Correlation with other variables¶

With "summary" (review summary)¶

Expect a high correlation since the summary should have similiar meaning as review

In [30]:
## calculate text vectors
df_summary_embedding = model.encode(df_review.iloc[:,-2])
df_summary_rdm = np.zeros((len(df_summary_embedding),len(df_summary_embedding)))
df_summary_rdm = pd.DataFrame(df_summary_rdm)
for i in range(0,len(df_summary_embedding)):
    for j in range(0,len(df_summary_embedding)):
        df_summary_rdm.iloc[i,j] = cosine_similarity([df_summary_embedding[i],df_summary_embedding[j]])[0,1]
        df_summary_rdm.iloc[j,i] = cosine_similarity([df_summary_embedding[i],df_summary_embedding[j]])[0,1]

summary_vec = melt_df(df_summary_rdm)
summary_review_corr = spearmanr(summary_vec, review_vec)
summary_review_corr
Out[30]:

        df_profile_rdm.iloc[i,j] = cosine_similarity([df_profile_embedding[i],df_profile_embedding[j]])[0,1]
        df_profile_rdm.iloc[j,i] = cosine_similarity([df_profile_embedding[i],df_profile_embedding[j]])[0,1]

profile_review_corr
Out[31]:
SpearmanrResult(correlation=0.04275385039204683, pvalue=1.447357228492148e-51)

In summary, the the semantic similarity can predict the similarity of scoring.
This may because high evaluations often contain positive description, and sentence transformer can sensitively detect it.
